Method prune()

The prune function checks if a candidate support point (theta_plus) is sufficiently different from the existing set of support points (theta) and within specified bounds (a, b). If these conditions are met, theta_plus is added as a new column to theta.

Usage

NPODObject$prune(theta, theta_plus)

Arguments

theta

A matrix of support points

theta_plus

A candidate support point

Method multi_D()

multi_D computes a likelihood-based metric, D_comp, by summing the probabilities from getPSI(), normalized by self$pyl. It starts with a penalty term of -N, calls getPSI(), and updates D_comp.

Usage

NPODObject$multi_D(theta_parameter)

Arguments

theta_parameter

A matrix of support points

Method getPSI()

getPIS The getPSI function calculates the probability of the observed data mprob is an N x K matrix where each entry [i, l] represents the probability of observing y[[i]] given the model prediction ySimList[[i, l]]. A small lower bound, 1e-100, is enforced for numerical stability.

Usage

NPODObject$getPSI(
  theta,
  ySimList = NULL,
  useLog = self$useLogNormalLikelihood,
  optimizeSigma = FALSE,
  lambda = NULL
)

Arguments

theta

A matrix of support points

ySimList

A list of model predictions

useLog

A logical to define if using log normal likelihood

optimizeSigma

A logical to define if optimizing sigma

lambda

A list of lambda values

Method getLikelihood()

Calculates the likelihood of the observed data, y, given the model predictions, ySim, and measurement error, sigma. The default case uses arithmetic error, but if use_log = TRUE, it calculates the likelihood using the logarithmic (ratio) error.

Usage

NPODObject$getLikelihood(y, t, theta, sigma, ySim, useLog = FALSE)

Arguments

y

A vector of observed data

t

A vector of time points

theta

A matrix of support points

sigma

A vector of measurement errors

ySim

A vector of model predictions

useLog

A logical to define if using log normal likelihood

Method multi_mu()

computes the model predictions for each individual in the study population given a set of support points, theta.

Usage

NPODObject$multi_mu(theta)

Arguments

theta

A matrix of support points
